    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. An escrow account is a financial arrangement where a third party holds and regulates payment of the funds required for two parties involved in a given transaction. In the context of buying a house, the escrow account is used to hold the buyer's funds until all the conditions of the sale are met. This ensures that the seller's property is transferred to the buyer and the buyer's funds are disbursed to the seller or their agent. The escrow agent, often a title company or an attorney, will manage the funds and documents, releasing them only when all the agreed-upon conditions are satisfied, such as the buyer securing financing, passing inspections, and completing the necessary paperwork. This process helps protect both the buyer and the seller by ensuring that the transaction is completed fairly and legally.",
