    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks that makes more sense. so if the money is just sitting there with a third party, what actually happens if there is a dispute or if something goes wrong with the house inspection right before closing? like how does the escrow agent decide who gets the money?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If there's a dispute or an issue arises with the house inspection right before closing, the escrow agent plays a crucial role in resolving the situation. The escrow agreement typically outlines the conditions under which the funds will be released. If there's a dispute, the parties involved can negotiate a resolution, which might involve repairs, price adjustments, or other remedies. If the dispute cannot be resolved, it may need to be settled in court or through arbitration, depending on the terms of the escrow agreement.\n\nIn the case of an issue with the house inspection, the escrow agent will hold the funds until the dispute is resolved. The buyer and seller can agree on a solution, such as the seller making repairs or the buyer accepting the property \"as is.\" If they can't agree, the escrow agent will not release the funds until the issue is legally resolved.\n\nThe escrow agent acts as a neutral third party to ensure that the terms of the escrow agreement are followed and that both the buyer and seller are protected. They will not decide who gets the money; instead, they will release the funds only when all conditions of the escrow agreement are met and the dispute is resolved. If the dispute cannot be resolved, the funds will remain in escrow until a legal decision is made.",
